Because of the piano's hegemony and its use of keys and hammers which create discrete notes, it treats # above C as equal with b below D and we are so taught. But on instruments with continuous ranges of notes like the violin, C# can be distinguished from Db. I believe some modern composers take advantage of this, as do some non-Western musical scales. 
The job of tuning instruments so that, for example, the key above C but below D produced a tone that was close enough to serve as either C# or Db was called "tempering".  Hence, my fellow Bach lovers, the work called "The Well-Tempered Clavier."

